<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="457" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,222,751]" pageId="6" pageNumber="457">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,273,222,247]" pageId="6" pageNumber="457">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Male. In the group VII key of 
<bibRefCitation author="Borgmeier" box="[651,858,222,247]" pageId="6" pageNumber="457" refString="Borgmeier, T. (1966) Revision of the North American phorid flies. Part III. The species of the genus Megaselia, subgenus Megaselia. Studia Entomologica, 8, 1 - 160." type="journal article" year="1966">
Borgmeier (
<number box="[790,850,222,247]" pageId="6" pageNumber="457" value="1966.0">1966</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[874,1010,223,246]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Megaselia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="457" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="creasoni">
<emphasis box="[874,1010,223,246]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="457">M. creasoni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
fails the key at couplet 
<number box="[1302,1330,223,247]" pageId="6" pageNumber="457" value="12.0">12</number>
where it matches 
<taxonomicName authority="Aldrich" authorityName="Aldrich" box="[250,457,258,283]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Megaselia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="457" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="minuta">
<emphasis box="[250,365,259,282]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="457">M. minuta</emphasis>
Aldrich
</taxonomicName>
in costal index (CI) but differs in having very lightly colored legs (
<figureCitation box="[1213,1281,258,283]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 9" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1896,1919]" captionTargetBox="[182,1436,264,1832]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[151,1436,247,1843]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 9. Habitus images (lateral). 1. Megaselia armstrongorum. 2. Megaselia bradyi. 3. Megaselia brejchaorum. 4. Megaselia carthayensis. 5. Megaselia ciancii. 6. Megaselia creasoni. 7. Megaselia defibaughorum. 8. Megaselia donahuei. 9. Megaselia francoae." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/242978/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="457">
Fig. 
<number box="[1266,1281,258,283]" pageId="6" pageNumber="457" value="6.0">6</number>
</figureCitation>
) compared to the dark mid and hing legs of 
<taxonomicName box="[486,601,295,318]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Megaselia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="457" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="minuta">
<emphasis box="[486,601,295,318]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="457">M. minuta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
